Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `NavigatingFrom`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    protected override void OnNavigatingFrom(NavigatingFromEventArgs args)
    {
        // Not yet cancelable in Shell's OnNavigatingFrom,
        // so the toolbar button + OnBackButtonPressed are
        // the primary guards.
        base.OnNavigatingFrom(args);
    }

    private async void ShowUnsavedChangesDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add a toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            IsVisible="True"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        IconOverride=""
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
        else
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
    BindingContext = this;
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` → handles Android hardware/swipe back; return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior` → replaces Shell's back arrow with a "Cancel" button whose tap you fully control via `Command`.
- The two together cover both the toolbar and the system back gesture.
